06831nam a22009495i 9780226748603DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020024755  a97802267486037 a10.7208/97802267486032doi  a(DE-B1597)571664  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJC423b.D629 2020 4aJC423b.D629 2021 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.97322300aDigital Technology and Democratic Theory /ced. by Lucy Bernholz, Rob Reich, Hélène Landemore. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Democracy and the Digital Public Sphere -- t2. Open Democracy and Digital Technologies -- t3. Purpose- Built Digital Associations -- t4. Digital Exclusion: A Politics of Refusal -- t5. Presence of Absence: Exploring the Democratic Signifi cance of Silence -- t6. The Artisan and the Decision Factory: The Organizational Dynamics of Private Speech Governance -- t7. The Democratic Consequences of the New Public Sphere -- t8. Democratic Societal Collaboration in a Whitewater World -- t9. From Philanthropy to Democracy: Rethinking Governance and Funding of High- Quality News in the Digital Age -- t10. Technologizing Democracy or Democratizing Technology? A Layered- Architecture Perspective on Potentials and Challenges0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most far-reaching transformations in our era is the wave of digital technologies rolling over—and upending—nearly every aspect of life. Work and leisure, family and friendship, community and citizenship have all been modified by now-ubiquitous digital tools and platforms. Digital Technology and Democratic Theory looks closely at one significant facet of our rapidly evolving digital lives: how technology is radically changing our lives as citizens and participants in democratic governments. To understand these transformations, this book brings together contributions by scholars from multiple disciplines to wrestle with the question of how digital technologies shape, reshape, and affect fundamental questions about democracy and democratic theory. As expectations have whiplashed—from Twitter optimism in the wake of the Arab Spring to Facebook pessimism in the wake of the 2016 US election—the time is ripe for a more sober and long-term assessment. How should we take stock of digital technologies and their promise and peril for reshaping democratic societies and institutions? To answer, this volume broaches the most pressing technological changes and issues facing democracy as a philosophy and an institution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aComputer networksxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aDemocracyxTechnological innovationszUnited States. 0aDigital communicationsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aInformation technologyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aassociations.  acollective intelligence.  adeliberation.  ademocracy.  adigital.  ajournalism.  aparticipation.  apublic square.  arepresentation.  atechnology.1 aAnanny, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernholz, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernholz, Lucy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCagé, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaplan, Robyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc